@* Counter — the Filament generator's INPUT. Phase 3.

   THIS FILE IS NOW PURE .razor. Both halves of it are COMPILED: the template by
   TemplateCompiler, the @code block by CSharpFrontEnd via Roslyn. Nothing in it is
   spliced verbatim into the output any more, and nothing in it is JavaScript.

   THE TEMPLATE AND THE @code BELOW ARE baseline/Counter.Blazor/App.razor's, VERBATIM.
   Not "equivalent to" -- the same text, and a test proves it rather than a comment
   claiming it: PureRazor_CounterRazor_IsTheBaselinesComponent compares this file's
   markup and @code against the baseline's, and the generator is separately run against
   baseline/Counter.Blazor/App.razor ITSELF -- the very file Blazor compiles -- and must
   emit an alpha-equivalent module. If the two sources ever drift, that is a failing test
   and not a footnote.

   THE BLANK LINES ARE PART OF THE SHARED DOM CONTRACT and must not be removed. Blazor's
   own compiler turns them into real "\n\n" text nodes (verified from its generated
   BuildRenderTree, which emits AddMarkupContent(0, "<h1 id=\"title\">Counter</h1>\n\n")).
   They are part of the contract precisely BECAUSE they are easy to drop without noticing
   -- which is what happened to the answer key, and cost a phase to find (decision 64).

   WHAT PHASE 3 CHANGED HERE, AND WHY THE OLD SHAPE WAS A MEASUREMENT PROBLEM.
   In Phase 2 this @code block held hand-written JAVASCRIPT: `const currentCount =
   signal(0)`. The template was compiled, but the STATE LIFTING -- deciding that a
   private int the template reads is reactive and must become a Signal -- was done by
   the author, in the input, by hand. So the one thing Phase 3 exists to prove was
   sitting OUTSIDE the measured bytes, doing its work before the compiler ever ran.
   It is inside them now: `private int currentCount = 0` below is lifted to
   `const currentCount = signal(0)` BY the compiler, and `currentCount++` inside
   Increment() is mapped to `currentCount.value++` -- one node in, one node out, no
   syntactic desugaring (samples/Counter/counter.js's header states that mapping).

   WHY currentCount IS REACTIVE, AND WHY THE RULE IS NOT "IT IS A FIELD".
   A field is lifted to a Signal iff the TEMPLATE READS IT and something ASSIGNS IT
   outside its construction site. currentCount is read by @currentCount below and
   assigned by Increment(), so it is lifted. A field the template reads but nobody
   assigns compiles to a plain create-time write with no signal and no effect; a field
   that is assigned but no binding reads stays a plain `let`. See CSharpFrontEnd's
   header for why only the conjunction reproduces both answer keys, and why that rule
   is also what closes decision 57's disclosed hole. *@

<h1 id="title">Counter</h1>

<p>Current count: <span id="counter-value">@currentCount</span></p>

<button id="increment" @onclick="Increment">Click me</button>

@code {
    private int currentCount = 0;

    private void Increment()
    {
        currentCount++;
    }
}
